Central Limit Theorem

Vladimir Mazin

My favorite distribution is Students t-distribution: \[F\left(x\right)=St\left(x, \nu\right)\] For this assignment Im using parameter values \[\nu=8\]

Lets take a sample of size 1000 from that distribution:

length <- 1000
x <- seq(-10, 10, length=length)
degf <- 8
dt_values = rt(length, df=degf)

Here is the histogram of the sample:

hist(dt_values)

Here is a smooth sample estimate of the density, and the actual population density for comparison:

Central limit theorem states that the distribution of a sample mean gets normal as sample size increases. Lets test that. For several values of \(n\) well take samples of size \(n\) from our distribution 1000 times, and calculate a sample mean for each sample. Well use histograms and kernel density estimates to compare the distribution of those sample means to the normal approximation suggested by the central limit theorem.

CLT states that sample mean has the same expectation as the original variable, and the variance \(\mathbb{D}\bar{X}_n=\frac{\mathbb{D}X}{n} = \frac{\frac{\nu}{\nu - 2}}{n}\)

Functions for generating data and conducting analysis:

create_sample = function(n) {
  l <- rep(0, 1000)
  for (i in 1:1000) {
    l[i] <- mean(rt(n, df=degf))
  }
  l
}

run_analysis = function(n) {
  sample_means <- create_sample(n)
  hist(sample_means)
  plot(density(sample_means), type="l",col="red")
  x_CLT <- dnorm(x, mean = 0, sd = sqrt((degf / (degf - 2)) / n))
  lines(x, x_CLT, col = "green")
}

For n=5:

#plot of the histogram, kernel density estimate and a normal approximation from CLT to compare 
n <- 5
run_analysis(n)

For n=10:

n <- 10
run_analysis(n)

For n=50:

n <- 50
run_analysis(n)
